        "severity": "caution",
        "source_facts": ["Issue description: ng-bootstrap (Patch von UVZUSLNVV-5824 muss berücksichtigt werden)"]
      },
      {
        "category": "dependency_risk",
        "boundary": "Pattern Library 12.6.0 deprecates the vertical action bar after PL 13.2.0. The upgrade must ensure the component still works and that no hidden breaking changes are introduced.",
        "severity": "info",
        "source_facts": ["Issue description: Vertical action bar is still being used (deprecated but still possible to use till PL 13.2.0)"]
      },
      {
        "category": "technology_constraint",
        "boundary": "Angular 19 upgrades RxJS to a newer major version; existing code that relies on RxJS 7.8.2 APIs must be checked for compatibility, especially any custom operators or pipe usage.",
        "severity": "caution",
        "source_facts": ["tech_versions.json: RxJS 7.8.2", "tech_versions.json: Angular 18-lts"]
      }
    ],
    "architecture_notes": "The UVZ system is split into five containers. The front‑end container hosts the presentation layer (≈287 components) built with Angular. Within this container, the Angular application imports the Pattern Library (shared UI component library) and communicates with backend services via HTTP/REST (application layer). The upgrade work is confined to the front‑end container, specifically the presentation layer components that depend on Angular core, Angular CLI, Webpack, Karma, and the Pattern Library. Neighboring components include:\n- Service proxies in the application layer (unchanged). \n- Shared UI components from bnotk/ds‑ng and the Pattern Library (must be updated to the new PL version). \n- Third‑party UI widgets (ng‑bootstrap, ng‑select, ag‑grid) that sit alongside the Angular core. \nThe developer will be \"here\": inside the front‑end container, updating the Angular version and all listed dependencies, then rebuilding the bundle with Webpack and re‑running the Karma test suite. No changes are required in the Java backend container or the infrastructure container.",
    "anticipated_questions": [
      {
        "question": "What Node.js and TypeScript versions are required for Angular 19?",
        "answer": "Angular 19 officially supports Node.js 18 LTS (or newer) and TypeScript 5.2+. The current project uses TypeScript 4.9.5, so both Node.js and TypeScript must be upgraded before the Angular packages can be installed."
      },
      {
        "question": "Is the existing ng‑bootstrap patch compatible with Angular 19?",
        "answer": "The patch was created for Angular 18. Compatibility must be verified; if it breaks, a new patch or an upgrade to a newer ng‑bootstrap version that supports Angular 19 will be required."
      },
      {
        "question": "Do we need to adjust the build pipeline (Webpack, Karma) for the new Angular version?",
        "answer": "Yes. Angular 19 may introduce changes to the Angular CLI build process and to the test runner configuration. Webpack and Karma versions should be reviewed and updated if they are not compatible with the new CLI."
      },
      {
        "question": "How can we confirm that the vertical action bar still works after the upgrade?",
        "answer": "Run the existing UI test suite that covers the vertical action bar, and manually verify the component in the Storybook (which still includes it up to PL 13.2.0). Any deprecation warnings should be logged but are not blockers until PL 13.2.0."
      },
      {
        "question": "Will RxJS updates cause breaking changes in our code?",
        "answer": "Angular 19 may upgrade RxJS to a newer minor version. Review the RxJS changelog for any removed operators or changed typings. Focus on custom pipe implementations and ensure they still compile with the upgraded RxJS version."
      }
    ],
